    "comprehension": null,
    "direction": null,
    "content": "<p>An asymmetrical periodic pulse train $v_{\\text {in }}$ of 10 V amplitude with on-time $T_{\\mathrm{ON}}=1 \\mu \\mathrm{~s}$ is applied to the circuit shown in the figure. The diode $D_1$ is ideal.</p>\n<p><img src=\"https://app-content.cdn.examgoal.net/fly/@width/image/jaoe38c1mh0r51kt/629a5a38-37fe-46d0-b5da-dec22cd9116d/37caaed0-ae97-11f0-b8e0-3b25f37f987e/file-jaoe38c1mh0r51ku.png?format=png\" data-orsrc=\"https://app-content.cdn.examgoal.net/image/jaoe38c1mh0r51kt/629a5a38-37fe-46d0-b5da-dec22cd9116d/37caaed0-ae97-11f0-b8e0-3b25f37f987e/file-jaoe38c1mh0r51ku.png\" loading=\"lazy\" style=\"max-width:100%;height:auto;display:block;margin:0 auto;max-height:40vh;vertical-align:baseline\" alt=\"GATE ECE 2021 Analog Circuits - Diodes Question 1 English\">The difference between the maximum voltage and minimum voltage of the output waveform $v_0$ (in integer) is $\\_\\_\\_\\_$ V.</p>",
    "options": [],
    "correct_options": [],
    "answer": "10to10",
    "explanation": "<p>$$ \\text { As mentioned we have } V_{\\text {in }}=10 \\mathrm{~V} \\text {; and Diode is } \\mathrm{ON} $$</p>\n<p><img src=\"https://app-content.cdn.examgoal.net/fly/@width/image/jaoe38c1mh0r50vq/aa0daba6-0a74-4a56-b03f-c7132459b968/3740e560-ae97-11f0-b8e0-3b25f37f987e/file-jaoe38c1mh0r50vr.png?format=png\" data-orsrc=\"https://app-content.cdn.examgoal.net/image/jaoe38c1mh0r50vq/aa0daba6-0a74-4a56-b03f-c7132459b968/3740e560-ae97-11f0-b8e0-3b25f37f987e/file-jaoe38c1mh0r50vr.png\" loading=\"lazy\" style=\"max-width:100%;height:auto;display:block;margin:0 auto;max-height:40vh;vertical-align:baseline\" alt=\"GATE ECE 2021 Analog Circuits - Diodes Question 1 English Explanation\">Capacitor gets charged up to 10 V .</p>\n<p></p>\n<p>So,&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;$$ V_c=10 \\mathrm{~V} $$</p>\n<p></p>\n<p>Also, we have&nbsp;&nbsp;$$ V_{\\text {in }}=0 ; \\text { Diode is } \\mathrm{OFF} $$</p>\n<p>For this, the Discharging time constant $=R C=10 \\mathrm{~m} \\mathrm{sec}$</p>\n<p>Then we can say</p>\n<p>$$ \\begin{array}{ll}  &amp; \\tau_{\\text {Discharges }} \\gg \\tau_{\\mathrm{OFF}} \\\\ &amp; V_c=10 \\mathrm{~V} \\\\ \\text { Also, } &amp; V_{\\text {out }}=V_{\\text {in }}-V_c=V_{\\text {in }}-10 \\\\ \\text { or, } &amp; V_{\\text {in }}=10 \\mathrm{~V} \\\\ \\text { or, } &amp; V_{\\text {out }}=0 \\mathrm{~V} \\\\ \\therefore &amp; V_{\\text {out }}=10 \\mathrm{~V} \\end{array} $$</p>\n<p>Hence, the correct answer is $(10$ to 10$)$.</p>",
    "topic": null,
    "year": 2021,
    "yearKey": "gate-ece-2021",
    "difficulty": null
  },
